The basic situation at Paramount Global is that National Amusements Inc., a=
 company controlled by Shari Redstone, owns roughly 5% of Paramount=E2=80=
=99s total stock, but roughly 77% of the voting stock. If you want to acqui=
re Paramount, what should you do? One option is to go to Paramount=E2=80=99=
s board of directors and propose a merger in which you pay cash to acquire =
all of the stock at a premium; the market capitalization of the stock right=
 now is about $8 billion, so this might require you to pay perhaps $10 bill=
ion or $12 billion.Another option, though, is to buy National Amusements=E2=
=80=99 stake. Again, National Amusements owns about 5% of the stock; if Par=
amount is worth $8 billion, then 5% of it is worth about $400 million. In f=
act the voting Class A stock trades at a higher price than the nonvoting Cl=
ass B stock, and you=E2=80=99d have to pay Redstone a premium, but still. M=
aybe you pay $1 billion or so for that stock. Or maybe you buy National Amu=
sements outright from Redstone =E2=80=94=C2=A0it also owns some movie theat=
ers =E2=80=94=C2=A0and pay $2 billion or so to get the Paramount stock plus=
 the movie theaters. And then you control 77% of the Paramount votes. And t=
hen you fire the board and take control and do what you want.Well. You don=
=E2=80=99t=C2=A0really=C2=A0fire the board and take control and do whatever=
 you want. Corporate law imposes some restrictions on what a controlling sh=
areholder like National Amusements can do with a public company like Paramo=
unt; if you bought National Amusements, you=E2=80=99d have some fiduciary d=
uties to other shareholders, and anything you did would be closely watched =
by those shareholders and the courts. And Paramount has a board of director=
s that is separate from National Amusements, with its own fiduciary duties =
to the nonvoting shareholders, and that board can make trouble. (It once tr=
ied to take away Redstone=E2=80=99s voting control!)So a third option is th=
at you could go to National Amusements and offer to buy it, but simultaneou=
sly negotiate with Paramount=E2=80=99s board of directors to try to get an =
all-around deal. Because what you really want is to acquire Paramount. Acqu=
iring 77% of the voting stock of Paramount gets you a long way toward that =
goal, but not all the way: You still have a board, judicial oversight, mino=
rity shareholders, etc. You want Paramount=E2=80=99s board and shareholders=
 to endorse your plans before you shell out billions of dollars for Nationa=
l Amusements.The Paramount deal talks over the last few months have involve=
d a consortium of bidders (Apollo Global Management and Sony Pictures Enter=
tainment) trying roughly the first approach, talking to Paramount=E2=80=99s=
 board about buying the whole company for cash, and another consortium (Sky=
dance Media, Redbird Capital and KKR & Co.) trying roughly the second appro=
ach, talking to Redstone about buying National Amusements but conditioning =
the deal on reaching an understanding with the Paramount board. That requir=
es some compromises: Skydance has to give the public shareholders something=
 to win over the Paramount board, and whatever value it gives them comes ou=
t of Redstone=E2=80=99s pocket. And in fact last week Skydance seemed to ha=
ve reached a deal with Paramount=E2=80=99s board, in which it would buy Nat=
ional Amusements and also pay some cash out to the public shareholders.But =
the ultimate fact of Paramount is that Redstone does control 77% of the vot=
es, and while she can=E2=80=99t do whatever she wants, she=C2=A0can=C2=A0bl=
ock whatever she=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0want. So the Wall Street Journal=
 reports:Shari Redstone =E2=80=A6 has ended discussions to sell her control=
ling stake in Paramount Global to Skydance Media and merge the two companie=
s, drawing to a close months of negotiations in one of the messiest deal dr=
amas to play out in recent years.National Amusements, the Redstone family c=
ompany that controls Paramount, said the parties had not been able to reach=
 a deal that would have given Skydance the keys to one of Hollywood=E2=80=
=99s most storied brands. The statement confirmed news first reported by Th=
e Wall Street Journal.Redstone=E2=80=99s decision marks a stunning about-fa=
ce, after she advocated behind the scenes for months for a deal with Skydan=
ce. She billed its backers=E2=80=94including CEO David Ellison=E2=80=94as t=
he best stewards for Paramount, owner of the namesake film studio, broadcas=
ter CBS and cable channels such as MTV and Nickelodeon.=C2=A0In the end, Re=
dstone had a change of heart, as trust frayed between the two sides. Redsto=
ne will now likely pursue a sale of just National Amusements, without tryin=
g to merge Paramount into another company, people close to her said.=C2=A0I=
n some ways that is the simplest solution. Reaching a deal that simultaneou=
sly satisfies Redstone and Paramount=E2=80=99s board is very tricky; every =
penny you give Redstone comes at the expense of public shareholders and vic=
e versa. Reaching a deal=C2=A0just to sell National Amusements=C2=A0is easy=
: That only has to satisfy Redstone. And then dealing with Paramount is the=
 buyer's problem.
