   =20
 =20
The most and least prestigious job in finance is =E2=80=9CI manage my famil=
y=E2=80=99s investments.=E2=80=9D One thing that it can mean is that you ha=
d a long (or, better, short) and lucrative career as a professional investo=
r, in which you learned all the skills you need to pick investments that go=
 up, and also made so much money that you don=E2=80=99t need to work at a j=
ob anymore. Instead, you took the money you earned at your job, used it to =
buy=C2=A0more investments that went up, got even wealthier, and now fund yo=
ur lifestyle by picking investments for an hour a week and otherwise play g=
olf and sail boats.Another thing it can mean is that you are just regular u=
nemployed, but you=E2=80=99ve got $200 in a Robinhood account, and you use =
that to YOLO GameStop options.
  [3]
If you are in the latter category, though, and when people ask you what you=
 do you say =E2=80=9CI manage my family=E2=80=99s investment portfolio,=E2=
=80=9D you will probably get into a few more parties than if you said=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99m unemployed so I mess around on Robinhood all day.=E2=
=80=9D=E2=80=9CI work at a family office=E2=80=9D is not=C2=A0quite=C2=A0th=
e same thing as saying =E2=80=9CI manage my family=E2=80=99s investments,=
=E2=80=9D but it=E2=80=99s not=C2=A0that=C2=A0far off either. Ordinarily a =
=E2=80=9Cfamily office=E2=80=9D means some sort of corporate entity, not ju=
st a personal account, but who=E2=80=99s going to check? And =E2=80=9Cfamil=
y office=E2=80=9D does imply, without saying, that your family=E2=80=99s in=
vestment portfolio is pretty big.Here=E2=80=99s a fun Bloomberg News articl=
e about=C2=A0fake family offices:From the conference halls of Singapore to =
events hosted by top Hong Kong officials, the ultra-wealthy clans that cont=
rol family offices in Asia are encountering a new and bizarre problem: fake=
 or exaggerated =E2=80=98peers=E2=80=99 created seemingly overnight with li=
ttle or no substance.The family office space has become so big, it=E2=80=99=
s attracting =E2=80=9Clegitimate players but also people trying to make a q=
uick buck or hustle,=E2=80=9D said Collevecchio, the managing director of O=
ppenheimer Generations Asia, a family office that represents a branch of th=
e clan that once controlled diamond giant De Beers. ...=E2=80=9CThis indust=
ry lends itself to frauds=E2=80=9D since it=E2=80=99s built on secrecy, sai=
d Francois Botha, founder of Denmark-based Simple, which services family of=
fices. =E2=80=9CNobody checks the credentials =E2=80=94 there=E2=80=99s qui=
te a lack of due diligence.=E2=80=9DI do not entirely understand the point =
of pretending to work at a family office, but I gather there are two main u=
se cases. One is that you pretend to be a sophisticated investor controllin=
g a large pile of wealth, and then use the trust that that engenders with=
=C2=A0other family offices to swindle them into co-investing with you in so=
me fraud that you have devised. The other is going to parties:For some, it=
=E2=80=99s a way to join the in-crowd, getting free access to conferences t=
hat would otherwise cost thousands of dollars. As one private equity invest=
or who had encountered several fakes put it: =E2=80=9Cthere is no party lik=
e a free conference party.=E2=80=9DI guess that's true, though I feel like =
there are=C2=A0better=C2=A0parties than a free conference party?
