e" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !import=
ant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-=
style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">require a 12.5% tranche thickness</a=
> for the first-loss tranche, so really JPMorgan would take $87.50 of the r=
isk and the SRT buyer and its lenders would split the other $12.50. And the=
n Duarte, Griffin and Arroyo report that =E2=80=9Cmarket participants surmi=
se that anywhere between 10% and 50% of the money for these deals could be =
borrowed,=E2=80=9D and that banks =E2=80=9Ccan typically provide up to 60% =
of the value of a trade through repo financing.=E2=80=9D So the lender woul=
d put up anywhere from $1.25 to $7.50 of the money, with the SRT buyer putt=
ing up the rest.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-2" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[2] This is loose, and in fact the repo lender=
 can issue margin calls if the loans start to default and hopefully protect=
 itself against this risk.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-3" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[3] A third thing it can mean is that your par=
ent or grandparent earned a ton of money, you got an MBA, and now you take =
monthly meetings with a staff of professional wealth managers. This is some=
where between the other two options in prestige, but honestly much closer t=
o the former. </p>
</div>
